ThinkPart(
    type='think',
    think='Let me now analyze everything I\'ve found:\n\n1. **Test failures in `
internal/biz/wapi`**: The failing tests (`TestUserUseCase_calcEnergyChargeCount`
, `TestUserUseCase_TryFilterUserSkillEcNotEnough`) are pre-existing and unrelate
d to this PR\'s changes. The PR only touches `mixing.go` and `market.go` in that
package, and those files don\'t have tests covering the new event publishing pat
hs.\n\n2. **Test coverage**: \n   - `internal/pkg/eventbus`: 79.3% ✅ (>= 70%)\n
  - `internal/biz/wapi`: 1.5% ❌ (but pre-existing)\n   - `internal/biz/wmix`: 0
% ❌\n   - `internal/biz/wcity/wcc`: 0% ❌\n\nWait, the requirement says "Biz 层
测试覆盖率 ≥ 70%". But which biz packages? The eventbus package has good coverag
e. The PR description says "单元测试覆盖率 83.9%" which refers to the eventbus p
ackage.\n\nHowever, `internal/biz/wmix` and `internal/biz/wcity/wcc` have 0% cov
erage. But these are existing packages - the PR just added event publishing to t
hem. Let me check if there were any tests before the PR.\n\nActually, looking at
the test output, `internal/biz/wmix` shows `coverage: 0.0% of statements` with n
o FAIL line, meaning there are no test files. `internal/biz/wcity/wcc` also show
s `coverage: 0.0% of statements` with no FAIL line.\n\nThe PR requirement says "
Biz 层测试覆盖率 ≥ 70%". If we interpret this as "the biz packages touched by th
is PR should have >= 70% coverage", then wmix and wcity/wcc fail. But if we inte
rpret it as "the new biz code added by this PR should have >= 70% coverage", the
n the eventbus package at 79.3% passes.\n\nGiven the context that this is a PR a
dding a unified event bus, the main new code is in `internal/pkg/eventbus` which
has 79.3% coverage. The changes to existing biz files are minimal (just adding e
vent publishing calls).\n\nLet me look more carefully at the architecture:\n\n**
Good things:**\n- Dependency injection is correct via Wire\n- `StreamPublisher` 
is an interface, properly injected\n- Data layer creates infrastructure, Biz lay
er receives interfaces\n- No cross-layer calls detected\n- Clean separation: Eve
ntBus (pkg) → Biz uses it\n\n**Issues found:**\n\n1. **Fragile error string comp
arison in `consumer.go`** (Line 97):\n   ```go\n   err.Error() != "BUSYGROUP Con
sumer Group name already exists"\n   ```\n   This is fragile because Redis error
messages can vary by version or locale. Should use `redis.HasErrorPrefix(err, "B
USYGROUP")` or a type check.\n\n2. **`EventAdapter` is a concrete struct used in
Biz layer** (Lines 34, 59 in `wapi/mixing.go`):\n   The Biz layer directly depen
ds on `*eventbus.EventAdapter` concrete type instead of an interface. This viola
tes the dependency inversion principle. The Biz layer should define its own inte
rface or use an abstraction.\n\n3. **Unused fields in `MarketUseCase`** (`wapi/m
arket.go`):\n   `publisher` and `eventAdp` are added to `MarketUseCase` but neve
r used to publish events. This is dead code. The constructor accepts a `publishe
r` parameter and stores it, but no method actually calls `b.publisher.Publish()`
.\n\n4. **Potential goroutine leak / panic issue in `bus.go`**:\n   ```go\n   b.
pool.Go(func() {\n       if err := h(ctx, event); err != nil {\n   ```\n   If ha
ndler panics, the gopool might swallow it or crash depending on configuration. N
o panic recovery.\n\n5. **`EventConsumerServer.Start` hides startup errors** (`s
erver/wapi/event_consumer_server.go`):\n   ```go\n   go func() {\n       if err 
:= s.consumer.Start(ctx); err != nil {\n           log.Context(ctx).Errorw("even
t consumer stopped with error", "error", err)\n       }\n   }()\n   ```\n   If `
Start` fails (e.g., can\'t create consumer group), the error is only logged. The
app continues running without the event consumer. This could be a fail-silent is
sue.\n\n6. **Unused import in `cmd/new_world_api/main.go`**:\n   ```go\n   "new-
world/internal/pkg/eventbus"\n   ```\n   Wait, is this used? Looking at main.go:
\n   ```go\n   bus eventbus.EventBus,\n   ```\n   Yes, it\'s used in the `newApp
` signature.\n\n7. **In `service/wapi/market.go` diff**: Only whitespace/formatt
ing changes. That\'s fine.\n\nLet me check if there are any other issues I misse
d.\n\nActually, looking at `internal/pkg/eventbus/bus.go` again:\n```go\nfunc (b
*internalEventBus) Publish(ctx context.Context, event *sharedpb.Event) {\n    ..
.\n    for _, h := range handlers {\n        b.pool.Go(func() {\n            if 
err := h(ctx, event); err != nil {\n                log.Context(ctx).Warnw("even
t handler failed", ...)\n            }\n        })\n    }\n}\n```\nThis captures
`h` and `event` in a closure loop. In Go, this is safe because the loop variable
s are per-iteration since Go 1.22. But wait - is this project using Go 1.22+? Le
t me check go.mod.',
